    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3917662199" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3917662199" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18643650-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591876752p2/18643650.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3917662199?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/18643650-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark?shelf=jackson">jackson</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3917662199" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10568241901698017547">I’ve got a thing for <b>Shirley Jackson</b>, it’s all a bit new, a bit exciting, some may say infatuated BUT after reading and really enjoying ‘Life Among the Savages’ and now being enthralled by her short story <b>The Lottery</b> I am really liking this author (yes, new to me) in a big way.<br/><br/>This short story is a mysterious piece which culminates in an ending which was totally unexpected.<br/><br/>The residents of a small country town take part in an annual “Lottery”. This involves a representative from each family draw</span>
  <span id="freeText10568241901698017547" style="display:none">I’ve got a thing for <b>Shirley Jackson</b>, it’s all a bit new, a bit exciting, some may say infatuated BUT after reading and really enjoying ‘Life Among the Savages’ and now being enthralled by her short story <b>The Lottery</b> I am really liking this author (yes, new to me) in a big way.<br /><br />This short story is a mysterious piece which culminates in an ending which was totally unexpected.<br /><br />The residents of a small country town take part in an annual “Lottery”. This involves a representative from each family drawing a paper from a box, the ‘winner’ is the one who draws one with a black dot. The members of the ‘winning’ family then re-draw with one of them becoming the ultimate winner by drawing the piece with the black dot. <br /><br />The writing is kind of light and breezy, almost surreal. A bunch of rural punters exchanging banter, kids playing and everyone being as they congregate in the square for the drawing of the “Lottery”.<br /><br />But there is a very dark undertone throughout, for me this manifested in a feeling of unease, but I didn’t really know why, the writing is such that Jackson puts us somewhere we don’t expect, nor want to go. But I was there and suddenly, I was smacked in the mush – and left sitting on my butt, stunned.<br /><br />There’s a real sense of quiet terror here, with a bunch of people, following an age-old tradition no matter what the cost. The theme of conforming, and following the mob is also apparent here – I am sure Jackson has countless other themes running through this nasty little piece – I am very much looking forward to learning more about this piece.<br /><br />I will have to leave it at that. I loved this story, it’s such a powerful piece.<br /><br />It can be found here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1948/06/26/the-lottery">https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/19...</a> in the New Yorker (audio too). <br /><br /><b>5 Stars5&gt;</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="10568241901698017547" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

