<div id="review_411672150" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/411672150" />
    <a title="Dave Schaafsma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/269235-dave-schaafsma"><img alt="Dave Schaafsma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610298533p2/269235.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/411672150?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dave Schaafsma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dave Schaafsma" href="/user/show/269235-dave-schaafsma">Dave Schaafsma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=fiction-20th-century">fiction-20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=halloween">halloween</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer411672150" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12959371267550587153">Happy Halloween month!<br/><br/>A classic horror short story from Jackson, widely anthologized, focused on the issue of conformity, and the banality of violence, in this case in a small town in New England. I have heard that Jackson’s (negative) experience living in North Bennington inspired this tale and maybe other stories that reflect negatively on respectable-seeming conservative people., but I do think her purposes are above a mere local grudge here. <br/><br/>When it was published in The New Yorker, it was at</span>
  <span id="freeText12959371267550587153" style="display:none">Happy Halloween month!<br /><br />A classic horror short story from Jackson, widely anthologized, focused on the issue of conformity, and the banality of violence, in this case in a small town in New England. I have heard that Jackson’s (negative) experience living in North Bennington inspired this tale and maybe other stories that reflect negatively on respectable-seeming conservative people., but I do think her purposes are above a mere local grudge here. <br /><br />When it was published in The New Yorker, it was attended by howls of confusion and rage and the gnashing of teeth. I like to imagine a literary world without “The Lottery," a world where the story bursts on to the stage, read by a world that has never experienced such an odd and disturbing phenomenon before. Very powerfully unsettling, told with real economy and subtlety. . . and finally, shock! One of the great short stories of all time, just paced perfectly, as we stroll causally to a conclusion unlike any we had seen before. Oh, there have been surprising endings, but nothing quite like this one, and people still don’t quite know what to do with it.<br /><br />Here you can see a Black and white 1969 version, care of YouTube, followed by the kind of baffled, wtf-type comments that the story seems to still engender:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HZyhVg31iaQ">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HZyhV...</a><br /><br />If you have never read it or might like to read it again, here it is:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://sites.middlebury.edu/individualandthesociety/files/2010/09/jackson_lottery.pdf">https://sites.middlebury.edu/individu...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="12959371267550587153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


